h3. Problem Definition

The [Migrating from Jira Server to Jira Cloud|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirakb/migrating-from-jira-server-to-jira-cloud-779160826.html] has this warning:
{quote}
Make sure you migrate to JIRA Cloud using the same timezone settings as your current server instance. Different timezones can cause problems with issue dates and issue creation after migration. For more information, see JRACLOUD-65305
{quote}

This is outdated, as we can no longer change timezone in Cloud and it may imply we can. The workaround is to set Server's timezone, by setting a parameter on Jira Startup. 

h3. Suggested Solution
 
Please, change this warning to this:
{quote}
Make sure you change JIRA Server's User Timezone to UTC before migrating. Using a different timezone can cause problems with issue dates and issue creation after migration. For more information, see JRACLOUD-65305
{quote}

h3. Summary
When an issue has statuses mapped to 2 boards, the "days in column" field does not reset when moving the issue to a column on the other board.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create an issue with a "complex" workflow;
# Create 2 boards, one with half of the workflow, other with the other half;
# Activate "days in column" field;
# Place the issue in a status and let it rest there for a couple of days;
# Transition the issue, so that it moves from one board to another;

h3. Expected Results
* The "days in column" field is reset, since it changed the status and, therefore, the column.

h3. Actual Results
* The "days in column" field keeps counting time, as if no change were made.

